 ('196', '120', '2', '1', 'it', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":\"2\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"James Suckling\'s Great Wines of Italy \",\"slug\":\"james-sucklings-great-wines-of-italy\",\"postDate\":1422921600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tLast week we attended two absolute great wine events:\\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n\\t James Suckling\'s Great Wines of Italy San Francisco, January 24th and James Suckling\'s Great Wines of Italy New York, January 26th. One could not have imagined a greater contrast between the two; we went from Sunny California, a super packed show and then to cold snowy New York the day went the city went into shut down mode because of the forecasted \\\"Historic Snow Storm\\\" which was not to be... here are a few pics from the shows.\\r\\n\\r\\n\\t\\r\\n<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\t<img style=\\\"width: 594px; height: 298.13px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Great-Wines-of-Italy-SF2.jpg#asset:118:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">\\r\\n<\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 284px; height: 439.61px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/great-wines-of-Italy-w-Gigetto2.jpg#asset:122\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\"><\\/p>\",\"25\":[\"121\"],\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-21 14:02:35', '2015-04-21 14:02:35', '3c9b447a-ad64-45a5-8bc1-2afa6fdbb962'),
 ('197', '99', '2', '1', 'it', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":\"2\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Spring time yet? April 7th, 2015\",\"slug\":\"spring-time-yet-april-7th-2015\",\"postDate\":1428426240,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Spring time yet? The sure sign that Spring is with us is when you see the buds germinating:  \\\"bud break\\\" time! <br><\\/p> \",\"25\":[\"110\"],\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-21 14:16:02', '2015-04-21 14:16:02', 'fa0f2d2d-af5b-454a-ae34-5ae633640d87'),
 ('198', '95', '2', '1', 'it', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":\"2\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"More on pruning, March 8th, 2015\",\"slug\":\"more-on-pruning-march-8th-2015\",\"postDate\":1425831960,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Back to Pruning? couple of weeks ago we mentioned that these cold winter months were spent pruning the vines and yes but today let\'s delve into the world of pruning a bit more: <\\/p><p>Here we have our Teroldego vines which we pruned differently than the Sangiovese. For the Teroldego we used a different pruning technique called Double Guyot.<\\/p><p>     <img style=\\\"width: 312px; height: 174.49px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/dougle-g-terrace-small.jpg#asset:94:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\"><br><\\/p><p>Basically we prune or train the vines to manage their world, their environment. The different techniques allow us to deal with leaf to fruit ratios, light vs shade, air movement, canopy, disease protection, and of course yield. <\\/p><p> In the bulk of the vineyard where Sangiovese grows we\'re doing \\\"spur pruning\\\" -- simply put the cordon or main branch of the vine has a bunch of spurs (mushroom like bumps) which each generate 2 fruiting canes (the thinner branches which produce the grape bunches). When we prune, we cut off completely the fruiting cane furthest away from the spur, and shorten the one closest to the spur, thus allowing next year\'s spur to generate 2 new fruiting canes. well that\'s the theory...<\\/p><p> With the Teroldego we did \\\"double guyot\\\" pruning. The main difference with the Guyot system is that it keeps a 2 year old cane to allow it to generate more fruiting canes (and thus potentially yield more fruit). It\'s used for less vigorous vine varieties to help yields. So at pruning, we cut off the 2 year old cane, and at the spur: the cane closest to the cordon is cut above two nodes, while the cane furthest away is shortened -- that cane will become next year\'s two year old cane. Only tweak is us doing \\\"double\\\" or \\\"bilateral\\\" meaning that we allow for two 2 year old canes, one on each side.<\\/p><p> That\'s the world of vine pruning in the winter time at La Noce!<\\/p>\",\"25\":[\"109\"],\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-21 14:17:15', '2015-04-21 14:17:15', '443fec9f-eb32-4915-a281-59cfa004cced'),
 ('199', '88', '2', '1', 'it', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"2\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Imbottigliamento di Pinko Pallino, 16 marzo, 2015\",\"slug\":\"pinko-pallino-getting-bottled\",\"postDate\":1426517400,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Visto che siamo ad inizio primavera, siamo finalmente pronti per imbottigliare il nostro attesissimo rosato, Pinko Pallino. Come \\u00e8 ben noto, il 2014 \\u00e8 stata una annata difficile ma che comunque ci ha dato la possibilit\\u00e0 di produrre un rosato piacevole, con ottima acidit\\u00e0 e freschezza, ma anche ben strutturato. Il rosato \\u00e8 rimasto per circa 7 mesi in vesche di acciaio con temperatura controllata a 12 gradi. Pinko Pallino quest\'anno \\u00e8 stato prodotto con una parte del salasso di Gigi\\u00f2 2014, il nostro vino rosso pi\\u00f9 pregiato, pi\\u00f9 l\'aggiunta di uve di prima vendemmia, adattissime per la produzione del vino rosato. Il risultato \\u00e8 un rosato di un bellissimo colore rosa pallido, elegante e profondo.    <\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 319px; height: 494.5px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Pinko-Pallino-bottled.jpg#asset:112\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">   <\\/p>\",\"25\":[\"105\"],\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-21 14:19:40', '2015-04-21 14:19:40', 'b93dbeaa-46b0-4a87-bf43-eace2457a781'),
